Defines the shared AST types for stage 1 of the steno compiler pipeline (source text → typed AST) and re-exports the two entry points implemented in sibling modules: `parse_source` (from `source.rs`) and `parse_template` (from `template.rs`); `expr.rs` backs the `%(EXPR)` grammar. This module itself contains no parsing logic — only the data model that `source.rs`, `template.rs`, and `expr.rs` build.

`Expr` represents a computed index `%(EXPR)` pre-reduced to linear form `a*d + b` where `d` is the repeat index — the parser is expected to have already collapsed any expression into this coefficient/offset pair; there's no general expression tree here. `Chunk` is the template AST: literals, structural braces (`Brace { open }}`), escapes (`Newline`, `Tab`), landing points (`Landing(u32)` for `%0`..`%9`, `Computed(Expr)` for `%(EXPR)`), and slots (`Dcount` `%d`, `TypeSlot` `%t`, `BodyBreak` `%b`, `Pattern` `%p`), plus `Repeat { sep, body }` for `%[ sep | body %]` where `sep` is joined between repeated items but never trails the last one. `Chunk::kind_name()` returns the DSL's own name for each variant (e.g. `"lit"`, `"repeat"`) for use in error messages/diagnostics — keep this in sync with any new `Chunk` variant.

`EntryFlags` bit-packs the boolean `@`-directives (`@multiline`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@fuse`, `@literal`) into a single `u8`; accessors are `const fn`. `set_named(&mut self, name: &str) -> bool` is the only writer, is `pub(crate)`, and is meant to be called exclusively by the directive parser in `source.rs`; it returns `false` (silently, no panic) for any unrecognized directive name rather than erroring — callers must check the bool themselves to report unknown directives. Adding a new boolean directive requires updating both the bit constant and this match arm.

`Entry` is one dictionary entry: `stroke` (key split on `/`), `stroke_raw` (as-written), parsed `template: Vec<Chunk>`, raw template text, optional `@count` key spec (`count: Option<String>` — weights are derived elsewhere from board geometry, not here), optional `@arity` for generic type entries, `flags: EntryFlags`, and the 1-based source `line` of the opening fence (for diagnostics). Downstream compiler stages (movement/count expansion, JSON emission — not in this module) consume `Entry`/`Chunk` directly, so changing these shapes ripples into whatever stage-2 module matches on `Chunk` variants or reads `Entry` fields.